      "id": "theory_oct_to_bin",
      "title": "Octal to Binary: Expansion Method",
      "content": "Converting octal to binary is even easier than binary to octal! Each octal digit simply expands into 3 binary bits.\n\n**The Expansion Method:**\n\n1. Take each octal digit one at a time\n2. Convert each digit to its 3-bit binary equivalent\n3. Combine all the 3-bit groups together\n4. Remove unnecessary leading zeros (optional)\n\n**Quick Reference Table:**\n0 = 000    2 = 010    4 = 100    6 = 110\n1 = 001    3 = 011    5 = 101    7 = 111\n\n**Example 1: Convert 247 (octal) to binary**\n\nStep 1: Convert each digit:\n  \u2022 2 = 010\n  \u2022 4 = 100\n  \u2022 7 = 111\nStep 2: Combine: 010 100 111\nResult: 010100111 (or 10100111 removing leading zero)\n\n**Example 2: Convert 52 (octal) to binary**\n\nStep 1: Convert:\n  \u2022 5 = 101\n  \u2022 2 = 010\nStep 2: Combine: 101 010\nResult: 101010\n\n**Example 3: Convert 777 (octal) to binary**\n\nStep 1: Convert each:\n  \u2022 7 = 111\n  \u2022 7 = 111\n  \u2022 7 = 111\nStep 2: Combine: 111 111 111\nResult: 111111111\n\n**Pro Tips:**\n\u2022 Each octal digit ALWAYS becomes exactly 3 bits\n\u2022 Don't forget leading zeros within each group!\n\u2022 For the leftmost octal digit, you can remove leading zeros from final result\n\u2022 Common values: 7=111, 0=000, 4=100\n\nThis is the fastest number system conversion because it's just direct substitution!"
    },
